    en: "New York law requires a landlord to give a written receipt for every rent payment made in cash, money order, or cashier's check. A tenant paying by personal check does not need a separate receipt — the canceled check is proof. The statute is Real Property Law 235-e. A landlord who refuses to give receipts puts the tenant at risk when a nonpayment eviction gets filed months later. Paying by money order and keeping every stub, or paying by check and saving the canceled copies, is the cleanest paper trail. A landlord who keeps refusing receipts can be reported to the Housing Council and to the Attorney General."
